The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Sunday, June 27, 2004 				 PM pet theme awaits CMs
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT				 	 Manmohan: Time to deliverNew Delhi, June 26: The first meeting of chief ministers called by the United Progressive Alliance (UPA) early next week will give Prime Minister Manmohan Singh an opportunity to carry forward his internal reform agenda and involve political leaders across the party divide in discussions to make the governments delivery system more effective.																								In keeping with the governments emphasis on rural India, the topic for discussion would be poverty alleviation and rural prosperity through panchayati raj or local self-government.																								The Prime Minister will not only inaugurate the two-day meeting but also interact personally with the chief ministers at least for half a day and listen to what they have to say on how best to ensure that the funds meant for peoples welfare reach the target groups.																								In his address to the nation on Thursday, Singh spoke at length on the need to reform government. His aides said the Prime Minister would use the opportunity to drive home the point that policies framed by the government should be implemented on the ground.																								Both state administrations and the local panchayats have to play a far more effective role and the conference will be the Prime Ministers attempts to get across to the state leaders the need to ensure that the government machinery works effectively.																								The Prime Minister will listen to the problems faced by the states and ask for their suggestions to tackle them.																								Rural development minister Raghuvansh Prasad, who along with panchayati raj minister Mani Shankar Aiyar will co-host the conference on Tuesday and Wednesday, said the meeting would be the first major step towards attaining the UPA objective of deepening and widening rural prosperity.																								The government hopes to reduce the poverty ratio by five percentage points by 2007 and provide gainful employment to the additional labour force. 																								The reduction in poverty ratio by five percentage points during the Tenth Plan and another 10 percentage points during the Eleventh Plan will still leave over 130 million people below the poverty line by 2012.																								The message for the states will be to ensure optimum use of funds allocated for existing programmes. 
